04539nam a22005535i 9780774856454DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748564547 a10.59962/97807748564542doi  a(DE-B1597)662157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.P3.B87 1996eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.1871 aHamilton, J. Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProphecy of the Swan :bThe Upper Peace River Fur Trade of 1794-1823 /cJ. Scott Hamilton, Knut R. Fladmark. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (234 p.) :b39 colour illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBefore the Fur Trade -- tFirst Nations of the Valley -- tThe Canadian Fur Trade and Peace River History -- tRediscovering History -- tRocky Mountain Fort -- tRocky Mountain Portage House and New Caledonia -- tSt Johns -- tYale and Mclntosh -- tArtifacts of the Fur Trade -- tThe Massacre of St Johns -- tPostscript -- tRocky Mountain Fort Journal -- tSt Johns Journal -- tArtifact Assemblages and Spatial Distribution of Rocky Mountain Fort and St Johns -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProphecy of the Swan covers twenty-nine years in the history of the Peace River valley in northeastern British Columbia. A vivid portrayal of life in some of the most isolated fur trade posts, it describes the intense competition between the North West and the Hudson's Bay companies, the individuals who were involved in exploration and commerce, and, finally, the shocking 'massacre of St. Johns.' It is unique in its integration of historic information and archaeological discovery, as it combines information recovered from many years of archaeological excavation with first-hand impressions of day-to-day life drawn from the few existing journals kept by company clerks. The authors focus not on the elites and middle management, but on the labourers and tradesmen, the wives and the children, whose lives were affected by the fur trade. Written for both a general audience interested in the history of British Columbia as well as fur trade scholars who will appreciate its innovative approach, this book brings new knowledge and insights to the study of this period in the province's history. Prophecy of the Swan also portrays life an archaeological project -- the endless hours of digging, the exacting work methods, and the small rewards inherent in discovery, as well as the mystique and romance that surround such an evocation of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFur tradezPeace River Region (B.C. and Alta.)xHistoryy18th century. 0aFur tradezPeace River Region (B.C. and Alta.)xHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aFladmark, Knut R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485645440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774856454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774856454/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-